|TOOL-RESULT|  "result": "## ER-Reason\nURL: https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.22919\n\n**ER‑Reason: A Benchmark Dataset for LLM Clinical Reasoning in the Emergency Room**\n\n**Abstract**  \nExisting benchmarks for evaluating the clinical reasoning capabilities of large language models (LLMs) often lack a clear definition of “clinical reasoning,” fail to capture the full breadth of interdependent tasks within a clinical workflow, and rely on stylized vignettes rather than real‑world clinical documentation. As a result, recent studies have found significant discrepancies between LLM performance on stylized benchmarks derived from medical licensing exams and their performance in real‑world prospective studies.\n\nTo address these limitations, we introduce **ER‑Reason**, a benchmark designed to evaluate LLM reasoning as clinical evidence accumulates across decision‑making tasks spanning the full workflow of emergency medicine.  \n* **Dataset**: 25,174 de‑identified clinical notes from 3,437 patients.  \n* **Workflow coverage**: triage intake, treatment selection, disposition planning, and final diagnosis.  \n* **Beyond diagnostic accuracy**: stepwise Script Concordance Test (SCT)–style questions grounded in real patient cases, assessing whether LLMs update their diagnostic beliefs in the correct direction and magnitude as evidence accumulates. These are scored against 2,555 emergency physician annotations.  \n\nWe evaluate reasoning and non‑reasoning LLMs on ER‑Reason and show that our tasks provide a more nuanced view of how LLM reasoning fails on real patient cases than existing benchmarks allow.\n\n**Citation**  \nMehandru, N., Golchini, N., Garg, N., LeSaint, K. T., Nash, C. J., Ramachandran, A., Zack, T., McCoy, L. G., Rodman, A., Bamman, D., Molina, M., & Alaa, A. (2026). *ER‑Reason: A Benchmark Dataset for LLM Clinical Reasoning in the Emergency Room*. arXiv:2505.22919. DOI: 10.48550/arXiv.2505.22919\n\n---\n\n---"
|TOOL-RESULT|}

