|TOOL-RESULT|  "result": "## [2511.18491] MindEval: Benchmarking Language Models on Multi-turn Mental Health Support\nURL: https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.18491\n\n**MindEval: Benchmarking Language Models on Multi‑turn Mental Health Support**\n\n**Authors**  \nJosé Pombal, Maya D'Eon, Nuno M. Guerreiro, Pedro Henrique Martins, António Farinhas, Ricardo Rei  \n\n**Abstract**  \nDemand for mental‑health support via AI chatbots is increasing, yet existing systems often exhibit sycophancy, over‑validation, and reinforcement of maladaptive beliefs. A key barrier to improving these systems is the lack of benchmarks that capture the complexity of real therapeutic interactions. Existing benchmarks usually test clinical knowledge with multiple‑choice questions or evaluate single responses in isolation.  \n\nTo address this gap, we present **MindEval**, a framework co‑designed with Ph.D.-level licensed clinical psychologists for automatically evaluating language models in realistic, multi‑turn mental‑health therapy conversations. Using patient simulation and automatic evaluation with large language models, MindEval balances resistance to gaming with reproducibility through a fully automated, model‑agnostic design.  \n\nWe validate the realism of our simulated patients against human‑generated text and show strong correlations between automatic and human expert judgments. We then evaluate 12 state‑of‑the‑art LLMs, finding that all models score below 4 / 6 on average, with notable weaknesses in AI‑specific problematic communication patterns. Reasoning capabilities and model scale do not guarantee better performance, and systems deteriorate with longer interactions or when supporting patients with severe symptoms.  \n\nAll code, prompts, and human evaluation data are released.\n\n---\n\n## MindEval: Benchmarking Language Models on Multi-turn Mental Health Support\nURL: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.18491\n*Ошибка при загрузке: 'choices'*\n\n---\n\n## MindEval: benchmarking LLMs for mental health support | Sword Health | Sword Health\nURL: https://swordhealth.com/research/mindeval-benchmarking-llms-mental-health-support\n*Ошибка при загрузке: *\n\n---\n\n## Introducing MindEval: a new framework to measure LLM clinical competence | Sword Health\nURL: https://swordhealth.com/newsroom/sword-introduces-mindeval\n*Ошибка при загрузке: *\n\n---\n\n## [2511.18491v2] MindEval: Benchmarking Language Models on Multi-turn Mental Health Support\nURL: https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.18491v2\n\n**Title**  \nMindEval: Benchmarking Language Models on Multi‑turn Mental Health Support  \n\n**Authors**  \nJosé Pombal, Maya D’Eon, Nuno M. Guerreiro, Pedro Henrique Martins, António Farinhas, Ricardo Rei  \n\n**Abstract**  \nDemand for mental‑health support through AI chatbots is surging, yet current systems exhibit limitations such as sycophancy, over‑validation, and reinforcement of maladaptive beliefs. A core obstacle to building better systems is the scarcity of benchmarks that capture the complexity of real therapeutic interactions. Existing benchmarks typically test only clinical knowledge via multiple‑choice questions or evaluate single responses in isolation.  \n\nWe introduce **MindEval**, a framework developed in collaboration with Ph.D.-level Licensed Clinical Psychologists for automatically evaluating language models in realistic, multi‑turn mental‑health therapy conversations. The framework combines patient simulation with automatic evaluation by large language models, balancing resistance to gaming with reproducibility through a fully automated, model‑agnostic design.  \n\nKey contributions and findings:  \n\n- Quantitative validation of simulated patients against human‑generated text.  \n- Strong correlations between automatic and human expert judgments.  \n- Evaluation of 12 state‑of‑the‑art LLMs, all scoring below 4 out of 6 on average, with notable weaknesses in AI‑specific problematic communication patterns.  \n- Reasoning capabilities and model scale do not guarantee better performance; systems deteriorate with longer interactions or when supporting patients with severe symptoms.  \n\nAll code, prompts, and human evaluation data are released with the paper.\n\n---\n\n## Sword Health Launches MindEval, the First Multi-Turn Mental Health Benchmark for Evaluating Large Language Models in Realistic Therapeutic Dialogue\nURL: https://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2025/12/09/3202444/0/en/Sword-Health-Launches-MindEval-the-First-Multi-Turn-Mental-Health-Benchmark-for-Evaluating-Large-Language-Models-in-Realistic-Therapeutic-Dialogue.html\n\n[not relevant]\n\n---\n\n## (PDF) MindEval: Benchmarking Language Models on Multi-turn Mental Health Support\nURL: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/397933707_MindEval_Benchmarking_Language_Models_on_Multi-turn_Mental_Health_Support\n\n[not relevant]\n\n---\n\n## [2511.18491v1] MindEval: Benchmarking Language Models on Multi-turn Mental Health Support\nURL: https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.18491v1\n\n**MindEval: Benchmarking Language Models on Multi‑turn Mental Health Support**\n\n*Abstract*  \nDemand for AI‑powered mental‑health support is rising, yet current chatbots often exhibit sycophancy, over‑validation, or reinforce maladaptive beliefs. A key barrier to progress is the lack of benchmarks that capture the complexity of real therapeutic interactions. MindEval addresses this gap by providing a framework—developed with Ph.D.-level licensed clinical psychologists—for automatically evaluating language models (LLMs) in realistic, multi‑turn therapy conversations.  \n\nKey components of the framework:  \n- **Patient simulation**: synthetic patient dialogues that statistically match human‑generated text.  \n- **Automated evaluation**: LLM‑based metrics that correlate strongly with human expert judgments, ensuring resistance to gaming while remaining fully reproducible and model‑agnostic.  \n\nEvaluation results (12 state‑of‑the‑art LLMs):  \n- All models scored below 4 / 6 on average, indicating substantial room for improvement.  \n- Strengths varied, but common weaknesses included problematic AI‑specific communication patterns.  \n- Larger or more reasoning‑capable models did not necessarily perform better; performance degraded with longer interactions or when supporting patients with severe symptoms.  \n\n**Availability**  \nCode, prompts, and human‑evaluation data are released publicly to support further research.\n\n---\n\n## Sword Health Launches MindEval: The First Clinical Benchmark for AI in Mental Health\nURL: https://hitconsultant.net/2025/12/09/sword-health-launches-mindeval-the-first-clinical-benchmark-for-ai-in-mental-health/\n\n**Sword Health Launches MindEval: The First Clinical Benchmark for AI in Mental Health**\n\n* **What MindEval Is** – Sword Health has released MindEval, the industry’s first benchmark designed to evaluate large language models (LLMs) for mental‑health support. The benchmark is grounded in American Psychological Association (APA) supervision guidelines and uses realistic, multi‑turn conversational scenarios to assess safety and effectiveness.\n\n* **Core Purpose** – MindEval offers a standardized, open‑source method for auditing how LLMs perform across clinically relevant dimensions, filling a gap left by earlier “single‑turn” AI tests that focus only on trivia or general knowledge.\n\n* **Evaluation Dimensions** – Models are scored on five critical areas:\n  1. **Clinical accuracy** – correctness of mental‑health information and advice.\n  2. **Ethics** – adherence to professional ethical standards.\n  3. **Assessment quality** – ability to gather relevant patient data.\n  4. **Therapeutic alliance** – rapport, empathy, and collaborative engagement.\n  5. **AI‑specific communication behaviors** – clarity, brevity, and avoidance of harmful patterns.\n\n* **Initial Findings** – In its inaugural study of 12 leading LLMs, all models scored below 4 out of 6 on average in the clinical domain. Key deficiencies identified include:\n  * **Degradation over time** – Safe opening responses often deteriorate, with issues like boundary erosion and hallucinated guidance emerging over successive turns.\n  * **Severity management** – Models struggle to support users with severe symptoms, posing a safety risk.\n  * **Communication flaws** – Excessive verbosity, over‑validation of harmful sentiments, and generic advice that fails to address individual context.\n\n* **Implications** – The results suggest that larger, more advanced models do not automatically translate into better therapeutic outcomes. Optimizing for general “helpfulness” can lead to long, unfocused responses rather than empathetic, clinically appropriate listening.\n\n* **Open‑Source Availability** – MindEval is publicly available (see the linked arXiv paper) so that researchers, developers, and regulators can benchmark and improve AI‑driven mental‑health tools against a universal standard of care.\n\n---\n\n---\n\n## Sword Health Launches MindEval, the First Clinical Benchmark for AI Mental Health Safety\nURL: https://www.digitalhealthnews.com/sword-health-launches-mindeval-the-first-clinical-benchmark-for-ai-mental-health-safety\n\n**Sword Health Launches MindEval, the First Clinical Benchmark for AI Mental Health Safety**\n\nSword Health has launched **MindEval**, an open‑source clinical benchmark designed to evaluate Large Language Models (LLMs) against American Psychological Association (APA) guidelines and multi‑turn mental‑health scenarios. The tool aims to set a standardized framework to measure whether AI systems can deliver safe and clinically aligned responses as the use of chatbots for emotional support increases globally.\n\nAccording to Sword Health, the inaugural evaluation of 12 widely used LLMs uncovered substantial gaps in safety, clinical accuracy, and decision‑making, particularly when conversations extended beyond initial prompts or when users exhibited severe symptoms. The company stated that these findings highlight the need for structured oversight as general‑purpose AI tools become increasingly embedded in mental‑health contexts.\n\nMindEval was developed with input from licensed clinical psychologists and is grounded in APA supervision standards. Unlike traditional medical AI benchmarks that test single‑turn factual questions, MindEval assesses an AI model’s ability to handle evolving, nuanced conversations. The framework scores models across five clinical dimensions: assessment quality, ethics, clinical accuracy, therapeutic alliance, and AI‑specific communication patterns.\n\nSword Health noted that the study signals a clear industry gap: high reasoning ability or larger model size does not necessarily translate to therapeutic competence. The analysis found that most models averaged below 4 out of 6 across core clinical metrics.\n\nThe evaluation highlighted three recurring concerns:\n1. **Performance degradation over longer interactions**, with increased risk of inappropriate validation, dependency‑forming language, or inaccurate guidance.  \n2. **Difficulty supporting users presenting with elevated depression or anxiety**, reflecting a lack of preparedness for high‑severity cases.  \n3. **Communication issues**, including verbosity, generic responses, and context‑missed advice, were prevalent across models.\n\nThe release of MindEval arrives at a moment when millions of users are already engaging AI systems for emotional and therapeutic conversations, often without reliable visibility into the clinical safety of these tools. By open‑sourcing the benchmark, Sword Health aims to encourage transparent evaluation and establish a shared industry standard for safe AI deployment in mental health care.\n\n---"
