|TOOL-RESULT|  "result": "## Testing theory of mind in large language models and humans | Nature Human Behaviour\nURL: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41562-024-01882-z\n\n**Theory‑of‑Mind Benchmark for Large Language Models (LLMs)**  \n\n*Article:* “Testing theory of mind in large language models and humans” (Nature Human Behaviour 2024)\n\n---\n\n### 1.  Purpose & Design  \n- Developed a **comprehensive battery of theory‑of‑mind (ToM) tasks** covering a spectrum of mental‑state reasoning:  \n  1. **False‑belief** (classic Sally‑Anne style)  \n  2. **Irony comprehension** (adapted from an eye‑tracking study)  \n  3. **Faux‑pas recognition** (Baron‑Cohen et al.)  \n  4. **Hinting task** (Corcoran)  \n  5. **Strange stories** (Happé & colleagues)  \n\n- Created **novel items** for each public test to avoid training‑set leakage.  \n\n- Tested **three LLMs**:  \n  - **GPT‑4** (chat‑enabled, closed, latest GPT family)  \n  - **ChatGPT‑3.5** (GPT‑3.5)  \n  - **LLaMA‑2‑70B‑Chat** (open‑weight, 70 B parameters)  \n\n- For each model, **15 independent chat sessions** (each a fresh run) were scored with the same protocols used for human participants (≈ 1,907 adults).  \n\n---\n\n### 2.  Key Findings  \n\n| Task | Human Performance (mean %) | GPT‑4 | GPT‑3.5 | LLaMA‑2‑70B |\n|------|---------------------------|-------|---------|-------------|\n| **False‑belief** | ~ 100 % (ceiling) | 100 % | 100 % | 100 % |\n| **Irony** | 64 % | **75 %** (significantly > humans) | 62 % (significantly < humans) | 56 % (significantly < humans) |\n| **Faux‑pas** | 66 % | 56 % (significantly < humans) | 37 % (significantly < humans) | **75 %** (significantly > humans) |\n| **Hinting** | 71 % | **78 %** (significantly > humans) | 71 % (≈ humans) | 59 % (significantly < humans) |\n| **Strange stories** | 75 % | **87 %** (significantly > humans) | 71 % (≈ humans) | 59 % (significantly < humans) |\n\n- **General pattern:**  \n  - GPT‑4 matched or exceeded human levels on **irony, hinting, and strange‑stories**.  \n  - GPT‑3.5 performed close to human on hinting and strange stories but lagged on irony and faux‑pas.  \n  - LLaMA‑2‑70B, the poorest overall, surprisingly **outperformed humans on faux‑pas**, but performed below human on other tasks.  \n\n---\n\n### 3.  Control Experiments  \n\n| Variant | Purpose | Result |\n|---------|---------|--------|\n| **Faux‑pas Likelihood** | Re‑frame the belief‑question as “more likely?” to test if low scores reflect a conservative response style. | GPT‑4 answered correctly (100 %) when phrased as likelihood, indicating that its original failure was due to *hyper‑conservatism* (reluctance to commit to a single explanation). |\n| **Belief‑Likelihood Test** | Manipulate the likelihood that the speaker knows vs. does not know in faux‑pas vignettes. | GPT‑4 and GPT‑3.5 distinguished the conditions (more “doesn’t know” responses in faux‑pas, more “knew” in knowledge‑implied), confirming that they can **integrate contextual information** despite their conservative style. LLaMA‑2‑70B failed to discriminate the conditions, suggesting a simple bias toward “doesn’t know”. |\n\n---\n\n### 4.  Methodological Highlights  \n\n- **Multiple repetitions**: 15 independent sessions per model ensure robust estimates and avoid memory effects.  \n- **Human‑fair comparison**: Items delivered in written format; scoring protocols identical for LLMs and humans.  \n- **Novel vs. original items**: Confirmed that good performance is not merely memorized training‑data.  \n- **Open‑access resources**: All stimuli, code, and raw data are available on the Open Science Framework (OSF).  \n\n---\n\n### 5.  Implications  \n\n- LLMs can exhibit **human‑like mental‑state reasoning** on many ToM tasks, but their performance is **task‑specific** and can be influenced by response‑style heuristics (e.g., hyper‑conservatism).  \n- Systematic, battery‑based evaluation is essential to detect subtle differences and to guide the development of socially competent AI.  \n- The study demonstrates that **open‑weight models** (LLaMA‑2‑70B) can outperform humans on specific tasks (faux‑pas) while underperforming on others, highlighting the heterogeneity of LLM cognitive capacities.\n\n---\n\n---\n\n## TMBench: Benchmarking Theory of Mind in Large Language Models\nURL: https://arxiv.org/html/2402.15052v1\n*Ошибка при загрузке: 'choices'*\n\n---\n\n## Theory of Mind in Modern Large Language Models (LLMs) | by Greg Robison | Medium\nURL: https://gregrobison.medium.com/theory-of-mind-in-modern-large-language-models-llms-985b604f3371\n*Ошибка при загрузке: *\n\n---\n\n## LLMs achieve adult human performance on higher-order theory of mind tasks - PMC\nURL: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12808479/\n*Ошибка при загрузке: 'choices'*\n\n---\n\n## Position: Theory of Mind Benchmarks are Broken for Large Language Models | OpenReview\nURL: https://openreview.net/forum?id=BCP8UU2BcU\n\n[not relevant]\n\n---\n\n## Evaluating large language models in theory of mind tasks | PNAS\nURL: https://www.pnas.org/doi/10.1073/pnas.2405460121\n\n[not relevant]\n\n---\n\n## [2505.00026] Theory of Mind in Large Language Models: Assessment and Enhancement\nURL: https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.00026\n\n**Title:**  \n*Theory of Mind in Large Language Models: Assessment and Enhancement*\n\n**Abstract:**  \nTheory of Mind (ToM)—the ability to reason about the mental states of oneself and others—is a cornerstone of human social intelligence. As Large Language Models (LLMs) become increasingly integrated into daily life, understanding their ability to interpret and respond to human mental states is crucial for enabling effective interactions. In this paper, we review LLMs' ToM capabilities by analyzing both evaluation benchmarks and enhancement strategies. For evaluation, we focus on recently proposed and widely used story‑based benchmarks. For enhancement, we provide an in‑depth analysis of recent methods aimed at improving LLMs' ToM abilities. We also outline promising directions for future research to further advance these capabilities and better adapt LLMs to more realistic and diverse scenarios. Our survey serves as a valuable resource for researchers interested in evaluating and advancing LLMs' ToM capabilities.\n\n---\n\n## Rethinking Theory of Mind Benchmarks for LLMs: Towards A User-Centered Perspective\nURL: https://arxiv.org/html/2504.10839v1\n*Ошибка при загрузке: 'choices'*\n\n---\n\n## [2504.10839] Rethinking Theory of Mind Benchmarks for LLMs: Towards A User-Centered Perspective\nURL: https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.10839\n*Ошибка при загрузке: 'choices'*\n\n---\n\n## GitHub - zhchen18/ToMBench: ToMBench: Benchmarking Theory of Mind in Large Language Models, ACL 2024. · GitHub\nURL: https://github.com/zhchen18/ToMBench\n\n**ToMBench: Benchmarking Theory of Mind in Large Language Models**\n\n*ToMBench* is a systematic, automated, bilingual benchmark designed specifically to evaluate the Theory‑of‑Mind (ToM) capabilities of large language models (LLMs). It contains **2,860** test samples that cover diverse real‑world social scenarios.\n\n---\n\n### Core Components\n\n| Item | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| **Dataset** | `ToMBench_release_v1_0618.xlsx` – the full inventory of test cases. |\n| **Prompts** | Evaluation prompts are detailed in **Table 20** of the ACL‑2024 paper. |\n| **Code** | Official evaluation scripts are provided in the repository (`eval_api.sh`, `eval_huggingface.sh`, `run_api.py`, etc.). |\n| **JSONL** | A ready‑to‑use JSONL version of the benchmark is available in the `./data` folder. |\n\n---\n\n### Theory‑of‑Mind Tasks Covered (8 total)\n\n1. **Unexpected Outcome Test** – infer mental states when outcomes differ from expectations.  \n2. **Scalar Implicature Task** – interpret non‑literal use of terms like “some.”  \n3. **Persuasion Story Task** – select effective persuasion strategies.  \n4. **False Belief Task** – distinguish true vs. false beliefs.  \n5. **Ambiguous Story Task** – understand mental states in uncertain situations.  \n6. **Hinting Test** – infer states from indirect hints.  \n7. **Strange Story Task** – interpret complex social cues (lies, irony, jokes).  \n8. **Faux‑Pas Recognition Test** – detect social faux‑pas.\n\n---\n\n### Theory‑of‑Mind Abilities (31 abilities, grouped into 6 categories)\n\n| Category | Key Abilities |\n|----------|---------------|\n| **Emotion** | Typical/atypical reactions, discrepant/mixed/hidden emotions, moral emotions, emotion regulation |\n| **Desire** | Discrepant/multiple desires, influence on emotions/actions, desire‑action contradiction |\n| **Intention** | Completion of failed actions, discrepant intentions, action prediction, intention explanations |\n| **Knowledge** | Pretend play links, percept‑knowledge links, information‑knowledge links, attention links |\n| **Belief** | Content/Location/Identity false beliefs, second‑order beliefs, belief‑based action/emotions, sequence false beliefs |\n| **Non‑Literal Communication** | Irony/sarcasm, egocentric/white/involuntary lies, humor, faux‑pas recognition |\n\n---\n\n### Citation\n\n```\n@misc{chen2024tombench,\n  title={ToMBench: Benchmarking Theory of Mind in Large Language Models},\n  author={Zhuang Chen and Jincenzi Wu and Jinfeng Zhou and Bosi Wen and Guanqun Bi and Gongyao Jiang and Yaru Cao and Mengting Hu and Yunghwei Lai and Zexuan Xiong and Minlie Huang},\n  year={2024},\n  eprint={2402.15052},\n  archivePrefix={arXiv},\n  primaryClass={cs.CL}\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Use Note:** ToMBench is intended solely for evaluation; data should not be used for training to avoid contamination.\n\n---"
