|TOOL-RESULT|  "result": "## ToMBench GitHub\nURL: https://github.com/zhchen18/ToMBench\n\n**ToMBench: Benchmarking Theory of Mind in Large Language Models**\n\n---\n\n### Overview\nToMBench is a systematic, automated, and original bilingual Theory of Mind (ToM) benchmark for LLMs, containing 2,860 testing samples involving diverse real‑world social scenarios.  \n- **Inventory file:** `ToMBench_release_v1_0618.xlsx`  \n- **Evaluation prompts:** Table 20 of the paper  \n- **Evaluation code:** Updated in this repository  \n- **JSONL data:** Available in the `./data` folder  \n\n**Important Notice**  \nUse ToMBench only for evaluation. Do not use the data for training to avoid contamination and inflated performance.\n\n---\n\n### ToMBench Framework\n- Covers 8 theory‑of‑mind tasks (see below).  \n- Maps to 31 specific ToM abilities from the ATOMS framework.  \n\n---\n\n### Theory‑of‑Mind Tasks\n1. **Unexpected Outcome Test** – Infer mental states when outcomes differ from expectations.  \n2. **Scalar Implicature Task** – Infer non‑literal meanings (e.g., “some” implying “not all”).  \n3. **Persuasion Story Task** – Understand and choose effective persuasion strategies.  \n4. **False Belief Task** – Distinguish own beliefs from others’ false beliefs.  \n5. **Ambiguous Story Task** – Gauge understanding in uncertain social vignettes.  \n6. **Hinting Test** – Infer mental states from indirect hints.  \n7. **Strange Story Task** – Infer mental states in stories with lies, misunderstandings, irony, or jokes.  \n8. **Faux‑pas Recognition Test** – Recognize social faux pas and norms.\n\n---\n\n### Theory‑of‑Mind Abilities (31 total across 6 categories)\n\n#### 1. Emotion (7 abilities)\n- Typical Emotional Reactions  \n- Atypical Emotional Reactions  \n- Discrepant Emotions  \n- Mixed Emotions  \n- Hidden Emotions  \n- Moral Emotions  \n- Emotion Regulation  \n\n#### 2. Desire (4 abilities)\n- Discrepant Desires  \n- Multiple Desires  \n- Desires Influence on Emotions and Actions  \n- Desire‑Action Contradiction  \n\n#### 3. Intention (4 abilities)\n- Completion of Failed Actions  \n- Discrepant Intentions  \n- Prediction of Actions  \n- Intentions Explanations  \n\n#### 4. Knowledge (4 abilities)\n- Knowledge‑Pretend Play Links  \n- Percepts‑Knowledge Links  \n- Information‑Knowledge Links  \n- Knowledge‑Attention Links  \n\n#### 5. Belief (6 abilities)\n- Content False Beliefs  \n- Location False Beliefs  \n- Identity False Beliefs  \n- Second‑Order Beliefs  \n- Beliefs‑Based Action/Emotions  \n- Sequence False Beliefs  \n\n#### 6. Non‑Literal Communication (6 abilities)\n- Irony/Sarcasm  \n- Egocentric Lies  \n- White Lies  \n- Involuntary Lies  \n- Humor  \n- Faux Pas  \n\n---\n\n### Results (Summary)\n- **Task‑oriented performance** and **ability‑oriented performance** of various LLMs are visualized (details in figures within the repository).  \n\n---\n\n### Citation\nIf you use ToMBench, please cite:\n\n```\n@misc{chen2024tombench,\n      title={ToMBench: Benchmarking Theory of Mind in Large Language Models},\n      author={Zhuang Chen and Jincenzi Wu and Jinfeng Zhou and Bosi Wen and Guanqun Bi and Gongyao Jiang and Yaru Cao and Mengting Hu and Yunghwei Lai and Zexuan Xiong and Minlie Huang},\n      year={2024},\n      eprint={2402.15052},\n      archivePrefix={arXiv},\n      primaryClass={cs.CL}\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### License\nMIT License (see `LICENSE` file).\n\n---"
|TOOL-RESULT|}

